[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] This is a collection of basic syntax elements with examples.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] At the end of every section, you'll find a link to a detailed description of the related topic.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] You can also learn all the Kotlin essentials with the free Kotlin Core track by JetBrains Academy.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] package my.demo import kotlin.text.* // ...
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] It is not required to match directories and packages: source files can be placed arbitrarily in the file system.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] The `readln()` function reads from the standard input.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] This function reads the entire line the user enters as a string.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] // Prints a message to request input println("Enter any word: ") // Reads and stores the user input.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] For more information, see Read standard input.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] In Kotlin, you declare a variable starting with a keyword, `val` or `var`, followed by the name of the variable.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] Use the `val` keyword to declare variables that are assigned a value only once.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] Use the `var` keyword to declare variables that can be reassigned.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] Kotlin supports type inference and automatically identifies the data type of a declared variable.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] You can use variables only after initializing them.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] You can either initialize a variable at the moment of declaration or declare a variable first and initialize it later.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] For information about declaring properties, see Properties.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] Inheritance between classes is declared by a colon (`:`).
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] For more information about constructors and inheritance, see Classes and Objects and instances.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] // This is an end-of-line comment /* This is a block comment on multiple lines.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] /* The comment starts here /* contains a nested comment */ and ends here.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] See Documenting Kotlin Code for information on the documentation comment syntax.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] A reference must be explicitly marked as nullable when a `null` value is possible.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] Nullable type names have `?` at the end.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] The `is` operator checks if an expression is an instance of a type.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] //sampleStart fun getStringLength(obj: Any): Int? { if (obj !is String) return null // `obj` is automatically cast to `String` in this branch return obj.length } //sampleEnd fun main() { fun printLength(obj: Any) { println("Getting the length of '$obj'.
[src:kotlin/basic-syntax] //sampleStart fun getStringLength(obj: Any): Int? { // `obj` is automatically cast to `String` on the right-hand side of `&&` if (obj is String && obj.length >= 0) { return obj.length } return null } //sampleEnd fun main() { fun printLength(obj: Any) { println("Getting the length of '$obj'.
[src:kotlin/classes] Like other object-oriented languages, Kotlin uses classes to encapsulate data (properties) and behavior (functions) for reusable, structured code.
[src:kotlin/classes] Classes are blueprints or templates for objects, which you create via constructors.
[src:kotlin/classes] When you create an instance of a class, you are creating a concrete object based on that blueprint.
[src:kotlin/classes] Kotlin offers concise syntax for declaring classes.
[src:kotlin/classes] You can keep both the class header and body to a bare minimum.
[src:kotlin/classes] An instance is created when you use the class as a blueprint to build a real object to work with in your program.
[src:kotlin/classes] It's possible to create instances wherever you need them, inside the `main()` function, within other functions, or inside another class.
[src:kotlin/classes] Additionally, you can create instances inside another function and call that function from `main()`.
[src:kotlin/classes] The following code declares a `Person` class with a property for storing a name.
[src:kotlin/classes] For information about creating instances of nested, inner, and anonymous inner classes, see the Nested classes section.
[src:kotlin/classes] When you create a class instance, you call one of its constructors.
[src:kotlin/classes] A class in Kotlin can have a primary constructor and one or more secondary constructors.
[src:kotlin/classes] The primary constructor is the main way to initialize a class.
[src:kotlin/classes] A secondary constructor provides additional initialization logic.
[src:kotlin/classes] Both primary and secondary constructors are optional, but a class must have at least one constructor.
[src:kotlin/classes] The primary constructor sets up the initial state of an instance when it's created.
[src:kotlin/classes] The primary constructor can declare parameters as properties.
[src:kotlin/classes] These constructor parameter properties are stored as part of the instance and are accessible from outside the class.
[src:kotlin/classes] It's also possible to declare primary constructor parameters that are not properties.
[src:kotlin/classes] The primary constructor initializes the class and sets its properties.
[src:kotlin/classes] In most cases, you can handle this with simple code.
[src:kotlin/classes] If you need to perform more complex operations during instance creation, place that logic in initializer blocks inside the class body.
[src:kotlin/classes] These blocks run when the primary constructor executes.
[src:kotlin/classes] Declare initializer blocks with the `init` keyword followed by curly braces `{}`.
[src:kotlin/classes] Add as many initializer blocks (`init {}`) as you need.
[src:kotlin/classes] You can use primary constructor parameters in initializer blocks.
[src:kotlin/classes] For example, in the code above, the first and second initializers use the `name` and `age` parameters from the primary constructor.
[src:kotlin/classes] A common use case for `init` blocks is data validation.
[src:kotlin/classes] In Kotlin, secondary constructors are additional constructors that a class can have beyond its primary constructor.
[src:kotlin/classes] Secondary constructors are useful when you need multiple ways to initialize a class or for Java interoperability.
[src:kotlin/classes] To declare a secondary constructor, use the `constructor` keyword inside the class body with the constructor parameters within parentheses `()`.
[src:kotlin/classes] In the code above, the secondary constructor delegates to the primary constructor via the `this` keyword, passing `name` and the `age` value converted to an integer.
[src:kotlin/classes] In Kotlin, secondary constructors must delegate to the primary constructor.
[src:kotlin/classes] This delegation ensures that all primary constructor initialization logic is executed before any secondary constructor logic runs.
[src:kotlin/classes] In classes with initializer blocks (`init {}`), the code within these blocks becomes part of the primary constructor.
[src:kotlin/classes] Given that secondary constructors delegate to the primary constructor first, all initializer blocks and property initializers run before the body of the secondary constructor.
[src:kotlin/classes] // Class header with no primary constructor class Person { // Initializer block runs when an instance is created init { // Runs before the secondary constructor println("1.
[src:kotlin/classes] First initializer block runs") } // Secondary constructor that takes an integer parameter constructor(i: Int) { // Runs after the initializer block println("2.
[src:kotlin/classes] Person $i is created") } } fun main() { // Creates an instance of the Person class Person(1) // 1.
[src:kotlin/classes] The visibility of this implicit primary constructor is public, meaning it can be accessed from anywhere.
[src:kotlin/classes] Class inheritance in Kotlin allows you to create a new class (derived class) from an existing class (base class), inheriting its properties and functions while adding or modifying behavior.
[src:kotlin/classes] For detailed information about inheritance hierarchies and how to use of the `open` keyword, see the Inheritance section.
[src:kotlin/classes] In Kotlin, abstract classes are classes that can't be instantiated directly.
[src:kotlin/classes] They are designed to be inherited by other classes which define their actual behavior.
[src:kotlin/classes] This behavior is called an implementation.
[src:kotlin/classes] An abstract class can declare abstract properties and functions, which must be implemented by subclasses.
[src:kotlin/classes] Abstract classes can also have constructors.
[src:kotlin/classes] These constructors initialize class properties and enforce required parameters for subclasses.
[src:kotlin/classes] An abstract class can have both abstract and non-abstract members (properties and functions).
[src:kotlin/classes] To declare a member as abstract, you must use the `abstract` keyword explicitly.
[src:kotlin/classes] You don't need to annotate abstract classes or functions with the `open` keyword because they are implicitly inheritable by default.
[src:kotlin/classes] For more details about the `open` keyword, see Inheritance.
[src:kotlin/classes] Abstract members don't have an implementation in the abstract class.
[src:kotlin/classes] In Kotlin, each class can have a companion object.
[src:kotlin/classes] Companion objects are a type of object declaration that allows you to access its members using the class name without creating a class instance.
[src:kotlin/classes] Suppose you need to write a function that can be called without creating an instance of a class, but it is still logically connected to the class (such as a factory function).
[src:kotlin/classes] If you declare a companion object inside your class, you can access its members using only the class name as a qualifier.
[src:kotlin/classes] For more information, see Companion objects.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] The Kotlin Standard Library provides a comprehensive set of tools for managing collections – groups of a variable number of items (possibly zero) that are significant to the problem being solved and are commonly operated on.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Collections are a common concept for most programming languages, so if you're familiar with, for example, Java or Python collections, you can skip this introduction and proceed to the detailed sections.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] A collection usually contains a number of objects of the same type (and its subtypes).
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Objects in a collection are called elements or items.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] For example, all the students in a department form a collection that can be used to calculate their average age.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Kotlin lets you manipulate collections independently of the exact type of objects stored in them.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] In other words, you add a `String` to a list of `String`s the same way as you would do with `Int`s or a user-defined class.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] So, the Kotlin Standard Library offers generic interfaces, classes, and functions for creating, populating, and managing collections of any type.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] The collection interfaces and related functions are located in the `kotlin.collections` package.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] The Kotlin Standard Library provides implementations for basic collection types: sets, lists, and maps.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Note that a mutable collection doesn't have to be assigned to a `var`.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Write operations with a mutable collection are still possible even if it is assigned to a `val`.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] The benefit of assigning mutable collections to `val` is that you protect the reference to the mutable collection from modification.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Over time, as your code grows and becomes more complex, it becomes even more important to prevent unintentional modification to references.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Use `val` as much as possible for safer and more robust code.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] The read-only collection types are covariant.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] This means that, if a `Rectangle` class inherits from `Shape`, you can use a `List<Rectangle>` anywhere the `List<Shape>` is required.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] In other words, the collection types have the same subtyping relationship as the element types.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Maps are covariant on the value type, but not on the key type.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] In turn, mutable collections aren't covariant; otherwise, this would lead to runtime failures.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] If `MutableList<Rectangle>` was a subtype of `MutableList<Shape>`, you could insert other `Shape` inheritors (for example, `Circle`) into it, thus violating its `Rectangle` type argument.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Let's walk through the interfaces and their implementations.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] To learn about `Collection`, read the section below.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] `Collection<T>` is the root of the collection hierarchy.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] This interface represents the common behavior of a read-only collection: retrieving size, checking item membership, and so on.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] `Collection` inherits from the `Iterable<T>` interface that defines the operations for iterating elements.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] You can use `Collection` as a parameter of a function that applies to different collection types.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] For more specific cases, use the `Collection`'s inheritors: `List` and `Set`.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] `MutableCollection<T>` is a `Collection` with write operations, such as `add` and `remove`.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] `List<T>` stores elements in a specified order and provides indexed access to them.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Indices start from zero – the index of the first element – and go to `lastIndex` which is the `(list.size - 1)`.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] List elements (including nulls) can duplicate: a list can contain any number of equal objects or occurrences of a single object.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Two lists are considered equal if they have the same sizes and structurally equal elements at the same positions.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] `MutableList<T>` is a `List` with list-specific write operations, for example, to add or remove an element at a specific position.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] As you see, in some aspects lists are very similar to arrays.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] However, there is one important difference: an array's size is defined upon initialization and is never changed; in turn, a list doesn't have a predefined size; a list's size can be changed as a result of write operations: adding, updating, or removing elements.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] In Kotlin, the default implementation of `MutableList` is `ArrayList` which you can think of as a resizable array.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] `Set<T>` stores unique elements; their order is generally undefined.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] `null` elements are unique as well: a `Set` can contain only one `null`.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Two sets are equal if they have the same size, and for each element of a set there is an equal element in the other set.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] `MutableSet` is a `Set` with write operations from `MutableCollection`.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] The default implementation of `MutableSet` – `LinkedHashSet` – preserves the order of elements insertion.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Hence, the functions that rely on the order, such as `first()` or `last()`, return predictable results on such sets.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] An alternative implementation – `HashSet` – says nothing about the elements order, so calling such functions on it returns unpredictable results.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] However, `HashSet` requires less memory to store the same number of elements.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] `Map<K, V>` is not an inheritor of the `Collection` interface; however, it's a Kotlin collection type as well.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] A `Map` stores key-value pairs (or entries); keys are unique, but different keys can be paired with equal values.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] The `Map` interface provides specific functions, such as access to value by key, searching keys and values, and so on.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] Two maps containing the equal pairs are equal regardless of the pair order.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] `MutableMap` is a `Map` with map write operations, for example, you can add a new key-value pair or update the value associated with the given key.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] The default implementation of `MutableMap` – `LinkedHashMap` – preserves the order of elements insertion when iterating the map.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] In turn, an alternative implementation – `HashMap` – says nothing about the elements order.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] `ArrayDeque<T>` is an implementation of a double-ended queue, which allows you to add or remove elements both at the beginning or end of the queue.
[src:kotlin/collections-overview] As such, `ArrayDeque` also fills the role of both a Stack and Queue data structure in Kotlin.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] Applications often need to perform multiple tasks at the same time, such as responding to user input, loading data, or updating the screen.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] To support this, they rely on concurrency, which allows operations to run independently without blocking each other.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] The most common way to run tasks concurrently is by using threads, which are independent paths of execution managed by the operating system.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] However, threads are relatively heavy, and creating many of them can lead to performance issues.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] To support efficient concurrency, Kotlin uses asynchronous programming built around coroutines, which let you write asynchronous code in a natural, sequential style using suspending functions.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] Coroutines are lightweight alternatives to threads.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] They can suspend without blocking system resources and are resource-friendly, making them better suited for fine-grained concurrency.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] Most coroutine features are provided by the `kotlinx.coroutines` library, which includes tools for launching coroutines, handling concurrency, working with asynchronous streams, and more.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] If you're new to coroutines in Kotlin, start with the Coroutine basics guide before diving into more complex topics.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] The `kotlinx.coroutines` library provides the core building blocks for running tasks concurrently, structuring coroutine execution, and managing shared state.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] Coroutines in Kotlin are built on suspending functions, which allow code to pause and resume without blocking a thread.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] The `suspend` keyword marks functions that can perform long-running operations asynchronously.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] To launch new coroutines, use coroutine builders like `.launch()` and `.async()`.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] These builders are extension functions on `CoroutineScope`, which defines the coroutine's lifecycle and provides the coroutine context.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] You can learn more about these builders in Coroutine basics and Composing suspend functions.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] Launching a coroutine from a `CoroutineScope` creates a context that governs its execution.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] These, along with other possible elements, make up the coroutine context, which is inherited by default from the coroutine's parent.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] This context forms a hierarchy that enables structured concurrency, where related coroutines can be canceled together or handle exceptions as a group.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] Kotlin provides several ways for coroutines to communicate.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] When multiple coroutines need to access or update the same data, they share mutable state.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] Without coordination, this can lead to race conditions, where operations interfere with each other in unpredictable ways.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] To safely manage shared mutable state, use `StateFlow` to wrap the shared data.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] Then, you can update it from one coroutine and collect its latest value from others.
[src:kotlin/coroutines-overview] For more information, see Flows, Channels, and the Coroutines and channels tutorial.
[src:kotlin/functions] Declare function parameters using Pascal notation: `name: Type`.
[src:kotlin/functions] Trailing commas help with refactorings and code maintenance: you can move parameters within the declaration without worrying about which is going to be the last one.
[src:kotlin/functions] You can make a function parameter optional by specifying a default value for it.
[src:kotlin/functions] Kotlin uses the default value when you call the function without providing an argument that corresponds to that parameter.
[src:kotlin/functions] Parameters with default values are also known as optional parameters.
[src:kotlin/functions] Optional parameters reduce the need for multiple overloads, since you don't have to declare different versions of a function just to allow skipping a parameter with a reasonable default.
[src:kotlin/functions] Overriding methods always use the base method's default parameter values.
[src:kotlin/functions] You can assign a parameter a default value that isn't constant.
[src:kotlin/functions] Parameters that refer to the values of other parameters must be declared later in the order.
[src:kotlin/functions] In this example, `len` must be declared after `b`.
[src:kotlin/functions] In general, you can assign any expression as the default value of a parameter.
[src:kotlin/functions] However, default values are only evaluated when the function is called without the corresponding parameter and a default value needs to be assigned.
[src:kotlin/functions] You can name one or more of a function's arguments when calling it.
[src:kotlin/functions] This can be helpful when a function call has many arguments.
[src:kotlin/functions] In such cases, it's difficult to associate a value with an argument, especially if it's `null` or a boolean value.
[src:kotlin/functions] When you use named arguments in a function call, you can list them in any order.
[src:kotlin/functions] You can also skip some arguments with default values, rather than omitting them all.
[src:kotlin/functions] You can pass a variable number of arguments (`vararg`) by naming the corresponding argument.
[src:kotlin/functions] When you declare a function with a block body (by putting instructions within curly braces `{}`), you must always specify a return type explicitly.
[src:kotlin/functions] The only exception is when they return `Unit`, in which case specifying the return type is optional.
[src:kotlin/functions] Kotlin doesn't infer return types for functions with block bodies.
[src:kotlin/functions] Their control flow can be complex, which makes the return type unclear to the reader and sometimes even to the compiler.
[src:kotlin/functions] However, Kotlin can infer the return type for single-expression functions if you don't specify it.
[src:kotlin/functions] The compiler can sometimes run into problems when inferring return types from single expressions.
[src:kotlin/functions] In such cases, you should add the return type explicitly.
[src:kotlin/functions] For example, functions that are recursive or mutually recursive (calling each other) and functions with typeless expressions like `fun empty() = null` always require a return type.
[src:kotlin/functions] When you do use an inferred return type, make sure to check the actual result because the compiler may infer a type that is less useful to you.
[src:kotlin/functions] In the example above, if you want the `double()` function to return `Number` instead of `Int`, you have to declare this explicitly.
[src:kotlin/functions] If a function has a block body (instructions within curly braces `{}`) and does not return a useful value, the compiler assumes its return type is `Unit`.
[src:kotlin/functions] `Unit` is a type that has only one value, also called `Unit`.
[src:kotlin/functions] You don't have to specify `Unit` as a return type, except for functional type parameters.
[src:kotlin/functions] You never have to return `Unit` explicitly.
[src:kotlin/functions] To pass a variable number of arguments to a function, you can mark one of its parameters (usually the last one) with the `vararg` modifier.
[src:kotlin/functions] Only one parameter can be marked as `vararg`.
[src:kotlin/functions] If you declare a `vararg` parameter anywhere other than last in the parameter list, you must pass values for the following parameters using named arguments.
[src:kotlin/functions] If a parameter has a function type, you can also pass its value by placing a lambda outside the parentheses.
[src:kotlin/functions] When you call a `vararg`-function, you can pass arguments individually, as in the example of `asList(1, 2, 3)`.
[src:kotlin/functions] You can declare functions that can be called without parentheses or the period by using the `infix` keyword.
[src:kotlin/functions] This can help make simple function calls in your code easier to read.
[src:kotlin/functions] Note that infix functions always require both the receiver and the parameter to be specified.
[src:kotlin/functions] When you call a method on the current receiver using the infix notation, use `this` explicitly.
[src:kotlin/functions] You can declare Kotlin functions at the top level in a file, meaning you do not need to create a class to hold a function.
[src:kotlin/functions] Functions can also be declared locally as member functions or extension functions.
[src:kotlin/functions] Kotlin supports local functions, which are functions declared inside other functions.
[src:kotlin/functions] For example, the following code implements the Depth-first search algorithm for a given graph.
[src:kotlin/functions] A local function can access local variables of outer functions (the closure).
[src:kotlin/functions] For more information on classes and overriding members see Classes and Inheritance.
[src:kotlin/functions] For more information on generic functions, see Generics.
[src:kotlin/functions] Kotlin supports a style of functional programming known as tail recursion.
[src:kotlin/functions] For some algorithms that would normally use loops, you can use a recursive function instead without the risk of stack overflow.
[src:kotlin/functions] This code calculates the fixed point of cosine (a mathematical constant).
[src:kotlin/functions] The function calls `cos()` repeatedly starting at `1.0` until the result no longer changes, yielding a result of `0.7390851332151611` for the specified `eps` precision.
[src:kotlin/functions] You can apply the `tailrec` modifier to a function only when it calls itself as its final operation.
[src:kotlin/functions] You cannot use tail recursion when there is more code after the recursive call, within `try`/`catch`/`finally` blocks, or when the function is open.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] Null safety is a Kotlin feature designed to significantly reduce the risk of null references, also known as The Billion-Dollar Mistake.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] One of the most common pitfalls in many programming languages, including Java, is that accessing a member of a null reference results in a null reference exception.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] In Java, this would be the equivalent of a `NullPointerException`, or an NPE for short.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] Kotlin explicitly supports nullability as part of its type system, meaning you can explicitly declare which variables or properties are allowed to be `null`.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] Also, when you declare non-null variables, the compiler enforces that these variables cannot hold a `null` value, preventing an NPE.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] Kotlin's null safety ensures safer code by catching potential null-related issues at compile time rather than runtime.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] This feature improves code robustness, readability, and maintainability by explicitly expressing `null` values, making the code easier to understand and manage.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] In Kotlin, the type system distinguishes between types that can hold `null` (nullable types) and those that cannot (non-nullable types).
[src:kotlin/null-safety] You can safely call a method or access a property on `a`.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] It's guaranteed not to cause an NPE because `a` is a non-nullable variable.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] To allow `null` values, declare a variable with a `?` sign right after the variable type.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] For example, you can declare a nullable string by writing `String?`.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] If you try accessing `length` directly on `b`, the compiler reports an error.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] This is because `b` is declared as a nullable variable and can hold `null` values.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] In the example above, the compiler requires you to use safe calls to check for nullability before accessing properties or performing operations.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] Read the next sections for details and examples of `null` handling tools and techniques.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] When working with nullable types, you need to handle nullability safely to avoid an NPE.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] One way to handle this is checking for nullability explicitly with the `if` conditional expression.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] In the example above, the compiler performs a smart cast to change the type from nullable `String?` to non-nullable `String`.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] It also tracks the information about the check you performed and allows the call to `length` inside the `if` conditional.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] Note that the example above only works when the compiler can guarantee that `b` doesn't change between the check and its usage, same as the smart cast prerequisites.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] The safe call operator `?.` allows you to handle nullability safely in a shorter form.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] The `b?.length` expression checks for nullability and returns `b.length` if `b` is non-null, or `null` otherwise.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] For example, Bob is an employee who may be assigned to a department (or not).
[src:kotlin/null-safety] That department may, in turn, have another employee as a department head.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] This chain returns `null` if any of its properties are `null`.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] In the example above, if one of the receivers in the safe call chain is `null`, the assignment is skipped, and the expression on the right is not evaluated at all.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] For example, if either `person` or `person.department` is `null`, the function is not called.
[src:kotlin/null-safety] When working with nullable types, you can check for `null` and provide an alternative value.
